    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "discussion",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Discussion",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "emphasis",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "Surface subdivision"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " is a technique for using low-detail geometry to generate a smooth surface for rendering. When you increase the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scngeometry/1524177-subdivisionlevel"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " value of a geometry, SceneKit automatically splits each face in the rendered surface, creating a more detailed, smoother geometry, as shown in "
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". SceneKit performs this subdivision process at render time, preserving the original geometry data."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "image",
              "identifier": "media-2929791",
              "metadata": {
                "anchor": "2929791",
                "title": "Figure 1",
                "abstract": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Rendering a subdivision surface "
                  }
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Subdividing a surface rounds away any sharp edges and corners in the geometry; however, such details may be important to a model’s design. To preserve edges, use the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scngeometry/1523246-edgecreaseselement"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property to identify edges and the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scngeometry/1523479-edgecreasessource"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property to specify how smooth or sharp they should appear after subdivision. To preserve corners, include a geometry source whose "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scngeometrysource/1523071-semantic"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " value is "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scngeometrysourcesemanticvertexcrease"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " when creating the geometry."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The default subdivision level is zero, specifying no subdivision—SceneKit renders the geometry exactly as its vertex data specifies."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
